                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.4112Anti-War/20: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Houghton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-05-02T11:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 2, 1928—11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 2—6:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>93. Your 104, April 30, 1 p.m. I am informed that purely as matter of tactics the
                    Government is now inclined to accept without serious discussion your proposal
                    and to approach the entire subject of reservations, interpretations, and similar
                    matters only after the antiwar treaty is signed. I am told also that the
                    Government will urge France to follow the same procedure on ground that too
                    great insistence now on reservations may endanger whole scheme and that the <pb
                        facs="0173" n="45" xml:id="pg_45"/> treaty must inevitably tend to maintain
                    the <hi rend="italic">status quo</hi> in Europe, the maintenance of which is, of
                    course, the dominant aim of French policy.</p>
                <p>I cannot vouch for the foregoing, but it does not seem unreasonable to suppose
                    that British mediation may take that line.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Houghton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
